summary.seg: This manuscript, probably copied in the last thirty years of the 17th century, is a copy of the commentary on Aristotle's Metaphysics by the 5th-century Neoplatonist philosopher Syrianus. The author was a native of Alexandria who studied at the Academy of Athens. He wrote commentaries, some of which are now lost, on various works of Aristotle and Plato, as well as on rhetorical and esoteric texts, and was the teacher of Proclus, the most important late Neoplatonist. The commentary on the Metaphysics is the most important surviving work of Syrianus. This copy, in a western European hand and probably produced in England, contains at the end an alphabetical list of names and texts mentioned in the work, perhaps an uncompleted index.

msItem.author: Syrianus
msItem.title: In metaphysica commentaria
msItem.filiation:
The manuscript was probably a copy of Oxford, Bodleian Library, MS Auct. T.1.16 (Misc. 194)
.
msItem.rubric: p. 1 Συριανοῦ τοῦ φιλοξένου, περὶ τῶν ἐν τῷ δευτέρῳ τῆς μετὰ τὰ φυσικὰ Ἀριστοτέλους πραγματείας λογικῶς ἠπορημένων καὶ διαίτης ἠξιωμένων
msItem.incipit: p. 1 Ἐν τῷ μείζονι αʹ τίς ἡ παροῦσα σκέψις εἰπών, ὅτι ἡ τοῦ ὄντος ᾗ ὄν
msItem.explicit: p. 219 πολλῶν δὲ ῥηθέντων ἐφ’ἑκάτερα λόγων, κρατοίη τῆς τῶν ἐντυγχανόντων διανοίας, τὰ ἀληθέστερα καὶ θεοφιλέστερα
msItem.note: On f. [vi] recto the copyist has written the author's name: Συριανος Αλεξανδρευς.

support.material: Western paper, folded in folio. Watermark: Fleur-de-lis ( 62 47 ) in the centre of the folio, comparable to Heawood 1670, 1672, but with a different countermark (HD). These examples are dated to 1683-1688.

supportDesc.foliation: The manuscript is paginated with the numbers [i-vi] + 1-220 + [vii-xii], in brown ink, in Arabic numerals, recto, upper right.

collation.p: It was not possible to determine the quire structure definitely.

supportDesc.condition: There is some creasing, slight water staining and areas of dirt.

handNote.p: The Greek text was copied in a western European mixed minuscule script, slanting to the right, in brown ink.
Punctuation used includes the middle and upper points and lower comma.

decoDesc.decoNote: On f. [vi] recto is a drawing in ink of a bird.
On ff. [v] recto and [vi] recto are simple friezes in brown and red ink.

additions.p: f. [iv] recto are notes in Greek and Latin including references to Simplicius's commentary on Aristotle's Physics.
Also marked on f. [iv] recto are the current classmark and the former classmarks 332, H.18 and O.10.22, the latter two struck through.
On ff. [vii] recto and [viii] recto-[viii] verso is an alphabetical list of names and works cited in the text, perhaps intended as an index but never supplied with page references.

binding.p: 18th-century binding with grey paper covering over couched-laminate boards, with a white parchment spine and plain pastedowns. The classmark appears on the spine on patches.

history.origin: The manuscript was probably copied between about 1670 and 1700, as suggested by the watermark. This is consistent with the style of script.
history.acquisition: Donated to Trinity College by the antiquary Roger Gale (1672-1744) Gale, Roger, 1672-1744 in 1738.
